<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Mr Andrew and Mrs Kathryn Curry (CYS0010)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mr Andrew and Mrs Kathryn Curry (CYS0010)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Ref: Session on Cycle Safety Debate on Monday December 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As tandem cyclists who average approximately 150 miles on, and off road, on our tandems each week we would like to put forward the following proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and experiences for road use.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cycle in a high volume H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GV area we have experienced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> very good driving by H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GV drivers and also very poor driving, unfortunately we have not been able to survey the drivers to ascertain the reason for poor driving.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">HGV Dri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">vers</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">    We would present the following proposals to the committee that have made a difference to the attitude of HGV drivers, and have received a positive response from the drivers such a sound of a horn, wave of hand or flash of lights;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When approaching </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a bend, hill or hazard we will, as soon as is reasonably practicable, get on to a safe location to allow the HGV to pass;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We always thank any motorist, however, especially HGV’s, who wait behind us for a safe place to pass;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">poor weather we will always </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> bright clothes, use lights and generally make ourselves as conspicuous as possible;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We always, in line with Institute of Advanced Motorist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cycling handbook, ride a metre </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from the curb;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> When passed very close by an HGV we don’t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> react by being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> offens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ive, aggressive or antagonistic;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(6)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also do not get involved in more than single file riding;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(7)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are, however, very poor HGV drivers/motorists who do need more education which should include face to face communication with cyclists who can explain the d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iscomfort, fear which comes from a large vehicle passing very close;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">General Road Use </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We continually read/hear on the news from drivers, media reports, newspapers who report the small number of cyclists who ignore the road rules, going through red lights,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> etc. However there is never any mention of the same frustrations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> experience:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Motorists who ignore red lights, have illegal number plates, drive extremely close to cyclists, sound vehicle horns when very close to cyclists, shout abuse at cyclists,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> fail to use lights in poor light conditions, use mobile phones, applying makeup, doing hair, setting sat-navs, talking to passengers, turning left/right immediately in front of cyclists, driving through puddles deliberately while passing cyclists, etc, et</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c. All of these actions cause frustration between cyclists and motorists and increase the animosity between both parties.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When so called celebrities make aggressive or negative comments about cyclists on TV, radio, in papers or magazines</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> animosity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">towards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cyclists on the road</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> increases.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Poor indication, or no indication, by motorists when turning or carrying out manoeuvres can cause a lot of frustration and puts cyclists at risk when approaching/passing a road junction;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Speed of motorists approaching road </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">junctions can be disconcerting as a cyclist is unaware if the driver has seen them and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> going to stop;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Poorly parked cars especially when the driver has stopped, with brake lights lit, and talking on the mobile phone, talking to passengers, etc. as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cyclist does not know what action the driver is going to take, pull off, park up, open the door;  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Motorists using cycle safe zones at traffic lights, pulling into and parking in allocated cycle lanes;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Training</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would suggest that vehicle learner drivers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have to get involved with cycle safety as part of the driver training programme and that schools have, as part of any curriculum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> road use, road safety, cycling for fitness/health/environmental improvement and driving with respect for all road users as pa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rt of cycling/road proficiency. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Law and Punishment</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The law/judges must start to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have a uniform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> approach to penalties for breaking the Road Traffic Act and impose stricter penalties for those who abuse the road and other road users. We hear of motorists wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o are still driving with high numbers of points on their licence which clearly gives the wrong impression to the individual given the points or other road users. There is very little action against those involved in hitting and killing/injuring cyclists, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hich very clearly gives the impression that a cyclist is likely to do less damage to their vehicle than hitting road furniture/other vehicle so is a soft target which will probably result in no action being taken against you should you hit one.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Finally</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re is an increasing number of motorist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and cyclist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> who really don’t care about others and will not alter or move from their planned actions/direction regardless of the consequences of doing so. They will sit with a hand on the car horn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, get verbal, use h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eadlights or sit on your rear bumper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should someone challenge their actions by getting in their way, lane, road junction, etc.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Parents and carers taking their children to school often drive with little or no consideration for other road users, even those w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">alking children to school. They may only drive for a very limited time each day and consequently don’t always have the skills learnt by other road users with more experience. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>